tation? explores one of the major issues in Holocaust studiesùthe intersection of memory and ethics in artistic expression, particularly within literature. As experts in the study of literature and culture, the scholars in this collection examine the shifting cultural contexts for Holocaust representation and reveal how writersùwhether they write as witnesses to the Holocaust or at an imaginative distance from the Nazi genocideùarticulate the shadowy borderline between fact and fiction, between event and expression, and between the condition of life endured in atrocity and the hope of a meaningful existence. What imaginative literature brings to the study of the Holocaust is an ability to test the limits of language and its conventions. After Representation? moves beyond the suspicion of representation and explores the changing meaning of the Holocaust for different generations, audiences, and contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBernard-Donals, Michael.1 aBolkosky, Sidney.1 aEaglestone, Robert.1 aEhrenreich, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aHartman, Geoffrey.1 aHorowitz, Sara.1 aLang, Berel.1 aMcGlothlin, Erin.1 aRothberg, Michael.1 aSchweitzer, Petra.1 aSpargo, R. Clifton, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aYoung, James.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813548159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813548159.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c